    <h3>The theorem program</h3>

    <p>
      Three theorems would close the triangle. Each is well-posed but unproven.
      Each builds on existing results from the adjacent fields.
    </p>

    <h3>Theorem 1: R-D bounds for journey observables</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Transfers:</strong> codec R-D optimization → TVG theory.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Setup:</strong> Fix a temporal graph model (e.g., temporal Erdős–Rényi
      with n vertices, edge density p, lifetime T). Fix an encoding family (timestamped
      edge list with quantized timestamps). Define distortion D(G, Ĝ) as the fraction
      of reachable pairs whose foremost journey duration stretches by more than factor α.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Question:</strong> What is R(D) — the minimum encoding rate that achieves
      distortion at most D?
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What exists:</strong>
      <a href="https://dl.acm.org/doi/abs/10.1145/1376616.1376661">Navlakha et al. (2008)</a>
      did this for static graphs under MDL (not Shannon R-D). Temporal spanners
      (<a href="https://drops.dagstuhl.de/entities/document/10.4230/LIPIcs.ESA.2022.19">Bilò et al. 2022</a>)
      give edge-count bounds for stretch-α preservation.
      The combination — information-theoretic R-D where distortion is on journeys — is open.
    </p>

    <h3>Theorem 2: Temporal sheaves</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Transfers:</strong> TVG formalism → sheaf cohomology.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Setup:</strong> Define a cellular sheaf F on a temporal event graph
      (Kivelä's weighted event graph, where nodes are temporal events and edges
      encode δt-constrained adjacency). Use Krishnan's semiring framework —
      Theorem 5.12 works over semirings, so the tropical semiring
      T = (R ∪ {"{"}&infin;{"}"}, min, +) is algebraically admissible.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Question:</strong> Does the sheaf-theoretic max-flow/min-cut on a
      temporal event graph with tropical coefficients yield a meaningful temporal
      reachability result? Specifically: does the duality gap measure something
      about journey fragility?
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What exists:</strong>
      <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1409.6712">Krishnan (2014)</a> proves MFMC
      over semirings on static digraphs. Temporal event graphs are static DAGs
      (Mellor's Lemma 3.2). The tropical semiring is a semiring. The ingredients
      compose — but nobody has checked whether the resulting duality gap says
      anything temporal.
    </p>

    <p>
      The <a href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9792072/">temporal
      state machines</a> invariance constraint sharpens this: temporal composition
      that breaks time-translational symmetry requires memory (state). If the
      sheaf's restriction maps encode this boundary, the cohomological obstruction
      might correspond to the stateless/stateful boundary in the TVG.
    </p>

    <h3>Theorem 3: Checkpoint spacing from H¹</h3>

    <p>
      <strong>Transfers:</strong> sheaf cohomology → codec engineering.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Setup:</strong> On a directed dependency graph (prediction DAG),
      define a cellular sheaf where the coboundary δ⁰ computes prediction residuals
      (<a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.11092">Seely 2025</a>: (δ⁰s)<sub>e</sub> = s<sub>v</sub> − W<sub>e</sub> s<sub>u</sub>).
      Hodge decomposition splits accumulated error into removable (im D) and
      irreducible (ker D<sup>T</sup> = H¹) components. Checkpoints are modeled as
      clamped boundary conditions on a subgraph.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Question:</strong> For a given dependency graph and prediction weights,
      what checkpoint spacing δ keeps dim H¹ (or ‖Hb‖) below a quality threshold τ?
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>What exists:</strong> Seely gives the complete operator dictionary for
      linear networks: coboundary, Laplacian, Hodge decomposition, learning gradient.
      Codec engineers know operationally that longer P-frame chains accumulate more
      error and that I-frame spacing is a quality/bitrate tradeoff. The algebraic
      form of the question is precise — dim H¹ as a function of sub-complex size —
      but nobody has computed it for codec-style dependency graphs.
    </p>

    <p>
      The linear restriction aligns with the prediction stage of codecs
      (motion-compensated subtraction is linear), though the full codec pipeline
      includes nonlinear stages. Nonlinear extension requires Jacobian linearization
      at equilibrium.
    </p>

    <h3>What this is and what it isn't</h3>

    <p>
      This is a Rosetta Stone, not a proof. Three fields study the same directed
      dependency structure with different operations. The three theorems above are
      the assembly instructions: well-posed questions with existing tools on each
      side, nobody working the seam.
    </p>

    <p>
      The vocabulary barrier is the obstacle, not the mathematics. The codec
      engineer's I-frame reset is the topologist's clamped sub-complex that
      zeros the harmonic component. The TVG theorist's chain fragility is the
      sheaf theorist's exactness failure. These connections have not been drawn
      in the literature because the three communities don't share venues.
    </p>

